From 127905b8a029c29b79a5765943b3c64ace50cc5b Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Alexandre Cordeiro <nenisdeno@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 21 May 2026 08:09:20 -0300
Subject: [PATCH] Metal: per-stream MTL::ResidencySet accessor on Device
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Adds an additive, lazily-allocated per-stream `ResidencySet` accessor
on `metal::Device`. The pre-existing device-global
`Device::residency_set()` is unchanged; this gives backends and
downstream callers a place to wire stream-specific allocations into
the GPU's wired pool without affecting the device-global set.

Motivation
----------

The existing CommandEncoder design already gives each stream its own
`MTL::CommandQueue` (created in `CommandEncoder::CommandEncoder()`),
so per-stream GPU scheduling already exists. But every stream's queue
shares one `Device::residency_set_` for wired-memory association,
which forces all model weights to compete for the same wired pool.

Backends that wish to wire stream-specific allocations (e.g. KV-cache
pages assigned to a particular model on a particular stream) can now
call `device.residency_set(stream_index)` to get a dedicated set
keyed by `stream.index`. Wiring this into a stream's queue (via
`queue->addResidencySet(...)`) is left to follow-up work — this PR
ships only the accessor + lifecycle hooks, which is the minimum
mergeable API surface.

API
---

  ResidencySet& residency_set(int stream_index);       // lazy create
  void release_stream_residency_set(int stream_index); // teardown
  void clear_stream_residency_sets();                  // bulk release

Existing `residency_set()` (no args) returns the device-global set
exactly as before.

Backward compat
---------------

Purely additive. Existing call sites compile and behave unchanged.

Tests
-----

`tests/test_metal_per_stream_residency.cpp` covers: distinct sets
for distinct indices, same index returns same set, distinct from
device-global, release deallocates, clear releases all. The test
file is gated under `_METAL_` so it skips cleanly on CUDA-only
or CPU-only builds.
